    think='Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the PR. Let me compile my
final review report.\n\nKey findings summary:\n\n**Blocking:**\n1. `im_bloc.dart
` temp message `senderId: null` - sent messages display as received in UI. This 
is a functional bug that breaks the core chat experience.\n\n**Major:**\n2. `im_
bloc.dart` pending message merge lacks deduplication - can cause duplicate messa
ges when switching conversations.\n3. `ConversationResponseDto` doesn\'t declare
`last_read_message_id` but service returns it - type mismatch/documentation inco
nsistency.\n4. `im_bloc.dart` doesn\'t update `id` field after message ack - tem
p messages retain client-generated UUID instead of server-generated UUID v7. Thi
s could cause issues with mark-as-read and message tracking.\n5. Design system f
ile naming inconsistency - missing `sw_` prefix on new component files.\n\nWait,
I need to be careful about #4. Let me re-examine:\n- Temp message: `id: clientMe
ssageId` (UUID v4 generated locally)\n- After ack: the handler only updates `seq
uenceId` and `status`, not `id`\n- The server returns `result.message.id` which 
is the server-generated UUID v7\n- But the ack event only contains `client_messa
ge_id` and `sequence_id`, not the server `id`\n\nLooking at `im.gateway.ts`:\n``
`typescript\nclient.emit("message:ack", {\n  client_message_id: payload.client_m
essage_id,\n  sequence_id: result.message.sequence_id,\n});\n```\n\nIt doesn\'t 
include `id`! So the client never learns the server-generated ID for the message
. This means:\n1. The message\'s `id` field in the BLoC remains the client-gener
ated UUID v4\n2. When `markAsRead` uses `lastMessage.id`, it sends the client-ge
nerated ID\n3. The server stores this client-generated ID as `last_read_message_
id`\n4. When broadcasting read receipt, the other user gets this client-generate
d ID\n5. The other user\'s `_messageIdToSequenceId` has this ID mapped (because 
it maps both `id` and `clientMessageId`), so it works for read receipts\n\nBut t
here\'s a problem: if the other user loaded messages from the API, the API retur
ns the server-generated `id` (UUID v7), not the client-generated `client_message
_id`. So the other user\'s message list has messages with `id` = server ID. When
they receive a read receipt with the client-generated ID, their `_messageIdToSeq
uenceId` map might have it if they also received the message via socket (which i
ncludes `client_message_id` in the payload). Looking at `MessageResponseDto`:\n`
``typescript\nexport class MessageResponseDto {\n  id!: string;\n  conversation_
id!: string;\n  sender_id!: string | null;\n  type!: string;\n  content!: string
;\n  client_message_id!: string | null;\n  sequence_id!: number;\n  status!: str
ing;\n  created_at!: string;\n}\n```\n\nYes, `client_message_id` is included in 
the response. So when Bob receives Alice\'s message via socket, the payload incl
udes both `id` (server UUID v7) and `client_message_id` (Alice\'s client UUID v4
). Bob\'s `_messageIdToSequenceId` maps both. When Alice sends a read receipt wi
th her own client-generated ID for her own message... wait, Alice is marking her
own messages as read? No, Alice marks Bob\'s messages as read.\n\nActually, `mar
kAsRead` is called with the `lastMessageId` of the last message in the conversat
ion. If the last message is from Bob, it\'s a received message with `id` = serve
r-generated UUID v7. If the last message is from Alice (a temp message), it\'s h
er own message with `id` = her client-generated UUID v4.\n\nIn normal usage, you
don\'t mark your own messages as read - you mark the other person\'s messages as
read. But the `ChatPage` calls `MarkAsRead` on `isInitialLoad` with `state.messa
ges.last`, which could be Alice\'s own message if she just sent one and it\'s at
the end of the list.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully:\n```dart\n
if (state is MessagesLoaded && state.isInitialLoad) {\n  _scrollToBottom();\n  /
/ Mark messages as read when opening conversation\n  if (state.messages.isNotEmp
ty) {\n    final lastMessage = state.messages.last;\n    if (lastMessage.id.isNo
tEmpty) {\n      context.read<ImBloc>().add(MarkAsRead(\n        conversationId:
widget.conversationId,\n        lastMessageId: lastMessage.id,\n      ));\n    }
\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis marks the very last message as read, regardless of who sen
t it. If Alice opens a conversation and the last message is from herself, she ma
rks her own message as read. This doesn\'t make sense semantically, but technica
lly it might work.\n\nHowever, if the last message is a temp message (her own, j
ust sent), then `lastMessageId` is the client-generated ID. The server accepts i
t and stores it. When broadcasting to Bob, Bob gets this client-generated ID. Bu
t Bob\'s messages don\'t have this ID - Bob\'s received messages have the server
-generated ID. Bob\'s `_messageIdToSequenceId` does have the client-generated ID
mapped (because when he received the socket event, it included `client_message_i
d`). So the read receipt would work.\n\nBut what if Bob loaded the conversation 
via HTTP API first, then the socket message came in? The API returns `id` and `c
lient_message_id`. So Bob\'s `_updateMessageCache` maps both. It still works.\n\
nWhat if Bob never received the socket event and only loaded from API? Then his 
`_messageIdToSequenceId` has the client-generated ID mapped because the API resp
onse includes it. It still works.\n\nSo the client-generated ID issue might not 
be a functional problem for read receipts. But it IS a problem for consistency -
the `id` field in the BLoC doesn\'t match the server\'s `id`. If any feature rel
ies on `message.id` being the server ID, it would break.\n\nFor now, I\'ll flag 
the `senderId: null` as Blocking, and the `id` not being updated as Major (since
it could cause subtle issues). But actually, let me reconsider whether the `id` 
issue is Major or Minor. Given that the current flow seems to work for read rece
ipts, it might be Minor. But it\'s still incorrect.\n\nLet me also check: is the
re any code that uses `message.id` to match with server-side data? The `markAsRe
ad` uses it. The `_messageIdToSequenceId` uses it. The `MessageAckReceived` uses
`clientMessageId` to find the message. So `message.id` is mostly used as a local
key. The server ID not being propagated might not break anything currently, but 
it\'s technical debt.\n\nI\'ll classify it as Major because it breaks the data m
odel consistency and could cause issues in future features.\n\nWait, I just real
ized another issue. In `im_bloc.dart`, `_onMessageAckReceived`:\n```dart\nemit(M
essageSent(messages: updatedMessages));\nemit(MessagesLoaded(\n  messages: updat
